export const articleBodies: Record<string, string> = {
  'cycle-decoded':
    'Your cycle is more than a period on a calendar. It is a monthly conversation between your brain, ovaries, and uterus—one that shifts with stress, sleep, illness, and time. Learning the rhythm does not mean obsessing over every day; it means noticing patterns so you can bring clearer questions to your clinician and to yourself.\n\nThe follicular phase begins when bleeding starts and estrogen slowly rises, preparing a follicle. Ovulation is the brief window when an egg is released, often accompanied by subtle signs like cervical mucus changes or a positive ovulation test. After that, the luteal phase begins: progesterone rises to support a possible pregnancy, and if conception does not occur, hormone levels fall and the next period arrives.\n\nTracking can be as simple as marking the first day of bleeding and how you feel, or as detailed as temperature and mucus notes. No method is perfect, and travel, shift work, or irregular cycles can make patterns harder to see. That is normal, not a personal failure. Apps that assume a 28-day cycle may mislead you—customize settings or treat predictions as guesses rather than facts.\n\nAt Lighthouse, we treat cycle literacy as self-advocacy. When you understand the phases, you can interpret test results, time conversations with your partner, and feel less lost when something shifts. You do not need to become a scientist—just a thoughtful witness to your own body, with compassion on the days the pattern wobbles.',

  'bbt-guide':
    'Basal body temperature tracking measures your temperature after a full night of rest, before you get out of bed. The idea is simple: progesterone slightly raises temperature after ovulation, so a sustained shift can confirm that ovulation likely happened. Many people find this reassuring; others find it stressful, and both responses are valid.\n\nTo start, use a thermometer sensitive to 0.1°F or 0.05°C, take your reading at the same time daily, and note sleep disruptions. Alcohol, illness, late nights, and heated bedrooms can nudge readings. A single odd temperature rarely means ovulation did not occur—look for a pattern across several days rather than one spike or dip.\n\nBBT cannot predict ovulation in real time; it confirms it after the fact. Pairing BBT with cervical mucus observations or ovulation tests often gives a fuller picture. If your chart looks rocky month after month, share images with your care team rather than diagnosing yourself from a screenshot alone.\n\nIf tracking feels like another chore on an already heavy journey, it is okay to pause. Lighthouse is here to help you choose tools that inform you without shrinking your life. The goal is understanding, not perfection on a graph—and your peace of mind counts as data too.',

  'luteal-phase':
    'The luteal phase is the stretch between ovulation and your next period—or a positive pregnancy test. Typically about 12 to 14 days in many cycles, it is when the corpus luteum produces progesterone to thicken the uterine lining and support early pregnancy. A shorter luteal phase sometimes gets discussed in fertility visits, but context matters more than any single number.\n\nDuring this phase you might notice breast tenderness, bloating, mood shifts, or food cravings. These sensations come from progesterone and are common, whether or not you are trying to conceive. If symptoms feel severe or cycle lengths vary widely, that is worth mentioning to a clinician rather than enduring quietly.\n\nIf you are tracking, a stable luteal phase pattern can help time tests and appointments. If you are in treatment, medications may change how this phase feels or how long it lasts. Bring your logs so your team can interpret them alongside blood work instead of guessing from memory.\n\nHowever you experience the luteal phase, remember it is a biological process—not a report card on your worth. Lighthouse encourages gentle observation: enough data to feel informed, enough compassion to rest when the wait feels long and your body asks for softness.',

  'role-not-small':
    'If you are the supporting partner, you may wonder whether your role truly matters when you are not the one taking medications or carrying a pregnancy. It matters deeply. Research on couples facing infertility consistently shows that emotional support, practical help, and shared decision-making improve coping and relationship satisfaction—even when biology centers one body.\n\nShowing up does not mean fixing everything. It can mean learning a few terms before an appointment, handling a pharmacy run, or sitting quietly when grief arrives without a schedule. Small, reliable gestures build trust: remembering injection nights, asking before sharing news with family, or protecting a rest day after a hard result.\n\nYour feelings belong here too. Disappointment, jealousy, fear, or numbness are common among partners and do not make you selfish. Finding your own outlet—a friend, therapist, or journal—helps you stay present without burning out. You are allowed to need care while giving care.\n\nLighthouse sees partners as co-navigators, not side characters. Your steadiness, curiosity, and respect for your loved one\'s body create the emotional climate where hope and honesty can coexist. Studies also link partner involvement with better adherence to treatment plans—remembering medications, attending visits, and sharing financial load. That presence matters even when you cannot fix the outcome.',

  'show-up':
    'Showing up in fertility is less about grand speeches and more about repeatable presence. On stimulation days, it might mean setting a gentle alarm and warming injection supplies. On waiting days, it might mean avoiding "any news?" texts and offering a walk instead. Consistency tells your partner they are not carrying the weight alone.\n\nAsk what help looks like this week—needs change. Some days your partner wants logistics; other days they want distraction or silence. A simple question like "Do you want solutions or company?" prevents well-meaning fixes from landing wrong when all they needed was to be heard.\n\nProtect your relationship from becoming only a medical project. Keep one ritual that is unrelated to treatment: a show you watch, a meal you cook together, a weekly check-in about feelings, not follicles. Intimacy can be affection, humor, and touch without pressure to perform sexually on a schedule.\n\nYou will not always get it right. Repair matters: apologize, adjust, learn. Lighthouse honors partners who keep returning with humility. Showing up well is a practice, not a personality trait—and every cycle gives you another chance to learn what your person actually needs. Small kindnesses compound across months of treatment in ways grand gestures rarely match.',

  'sperm-health':
    'Sperm health is half of the conception equation and still under-discussed. Sperm take about 70 to 90 days to develop, which means lifestyle changes you make today may show up in samples months later. A semen analysis measures count, movement, and shape—it is a snapshot, not a verdict on anyone\'s masculinity or value.\n\nHeat, smoking, heavy alcohol use, certain medications, and untreated infections can affect results. A reproductive urologist can look for varicocele, hormonal issues, or genetic factors when numbers are low or fertilization struggles appear in treatment. Diet rich in antioxidants, regular movement, and adequate sleep support overall health, including sperm.\n\nAbstinence timing before a test matters: usually two to five days of abstinence, per clinic guidance. Repeated testing is common because numbers vary. If IVF or ICSI is recommended, that is a pathway, not a punishment—and it does not erase the possibility of biological fatherhood.\n\nAt Lighthouse, we speak about sperm health plainly and without shame. Partners deserve information, agency, and respect—because improving odds is a team effort, not a secret burden carried by one person. If work exposes you to heat or chemicals, mention it at visits so your team can factor it in. Repeat testing after lifestyle changes gives a clearer picture than one sample alone.',

  'timing-not-everything':
    'Timing intercourse or insemination around ovulation helps, but it is not the whole story. Healthy couples under 35 still have only about a 20–25% chance each cycle even with good timing. That math surprises many people and can ease the guilt that builds when months pass without a positive test.\n\nFertile windows are wider than a single hour. Sperm can live several days in fertile cervical mucus, while the egg is viable for roughly 12 to 24 hours after ovulation. Tracking mucus, ovulation tests, or ultrasound monitoring can narrow the window without turning sex into a rigid chore—unless that structure works for you.\n\nIf timing feels stressful, consider alternating planned nights with connection that is not goal-driven. Clinics can advise on frequency after procedures or when to avoid pressure. If cycles are irregular, medical evaluation often helps more than another app notification pinging at midnight.\n\nLighthouse reminds you that love, biology, and luck intertwine. You can be doing everything "right" and still need more time or more care—and that does not mean your body is broken. If you have a 28-day cycle, ovulation often lands around day 14, but "often" is not "always." Give yourself credit for showing up to a process that asks a lot of patience.',

  'six-months-in':
    'Six months of trying can feel like both a blink and an eternity. If you are under 35 with regular cycles, many guidelines suggest checking in with a clinician around the one-year mark—but you can seek care sooner if something worries you: painful periods, irregular cycles, known conditions, or prior pregnancy loss. If you are 35 or older, earlier evaluation is often recommended.\n\nThis milestone is a good moment to gather data: cycle length, ovulation signs, any tests already done, and lifestyle factors like sleep and smoking. Bring your partner into the conversation if you are building a family together; their health history matters too. A simple calendar of first bleed days is already useful.\n\nEmotionally, six months is when friends\' announcements can sting and "just relax" advice starts to land like insults. Your frustration is valid. Support groups, therapy, or a trusted friend who listens without fixing can prevent isolation from becoming its own kind of pain.\n\nLighthouse normalizes both patience and advocacy. You do not have to wait in silence until a calendar says you have suffered enough to deserve help. Before your visit, list questions: Should we test now? What would you check first? What timeline makes sense for us?',

  'stress-fertility-loop':
    'Stress and fertility influence each other in a loop that is biological and emotional. Stress hormones can subtly affect ovulation and sleep; fertility struggles raise anxiety, which makes rest harder. Naming the loop is not blaming you—it is explaining why "just relax" is neither kind nor complete science.\n\nSmall nervous-system supports help: predictable bedtimes, brief walks, limited doom-scrolling before sleep, or a five-minute breathing practice you will actually use. Therapy, especially approaches like CBT or ACT, can reduce the grip of catastrophic thoughts without forcing toxic positivity or pretending feelings do not exist.\n\nMedical teams can also reduce stress by clarifying next steps, explaining side effects, and giving realistic timelines. Ask for written summaries after visits if your mind goes blank. Knowing what to expect next week often lowers the hum of background dread.\n\nYou are allowed to grieve and to hope in the same hour. Lighthouse treats stress care as fertility care—not a luxury, but part of staying in your body while you pursue parenthood. Body-based practices—gentle yoga, stretching, humming breath—can lower physiological arousal without requiring a spa day. Even five minutes of quiet before a monitoring appointment counts as care, not indulgence. Stress support belongs in every treatment plan.',

  'fertility-diet':
    'No single food guarantees pregnancy, but nourishment supports the hormones, blood sugar, and inflammation balance that fertility needs. Patterns linked with better outcomes in research include plenty of vegetables, whole grains, legumes, nuts, olive oil, and lean proteins—think Mediterranean-style plates rather than punishing restriction.\n\nFolic acid or methylfolate matters before conception for neural tube development; many clinicians recommend 400–800 mcg daily, with higher doses for some histories. Omega-3s from fish or algae, adequate iron, and vitamin D when levels are low are common conversations in preconception visits.\n\nExtreme diets, fasting beyond medical guidance, or cutting entire food groups without reason can backfire. If you have PCOS, insulin resistance, or endometriosis, personalized advice beats generic lists. A dietitian familiar with fertility can translate labs into meals you will actually eat.\n\nLighthouse invites you to eat with steadiness, not fear. Food is fuel for a long journey—one that deserves satisfaction as well as science. For people with PCOS, pairing protein and fiber at meals may steady blood sugar; for endometriosis, anti-inflammatory patterns sometimes feel helpful even when evidence is mixed. Pleasure at the table is not the enemy of preparation—it helps you sustain the long haul. Nourishment and joy can share the same plate.',

  'sleep-fertility':
    'Sleep is when your body repairs, regulates hormones, and processes emotion. Short or fragmented sleep is associated with irregular cycles, higher perceived stress, and lower quality of life during treatment—not because you failed a wellness trend, but because biology needs rest to do its intricate work.\n\nAim for a consistent wake time, dim lights an hour before bed, and a cooler, dark room. If stimulant medications or progesterone affect sleep in IVF, tell your team; adjustments or short-term aids may be options. Night shifts and parenting schedules complicate sleep—practical tweaks like blackout curtains or eye masks can help without perfection.\n\nIf you lie awake cycling through worries, a notebook by the bed to park tomorrow\'s tasks can ease the spin. Therapy and mindfulness apps are tools, not judgments. Protecting even one extra hour of rest during stimulation is an act of care, not laziness.\n\nYou deserve rest even when conception has not happened yet. Lighthouse treats sleep as part of the protocol of being human—not a bonus for when the journey is over. Screen curfews, white noise, and keeping the bedroom cool are low-cost experiments worth trying before you blame yourself. Rest is not something you earn with a positive test—it is something your body needs while you wait for one.',

  'lifestyle-changes':
    'Lifestyle changes can improve fertility health without erasing joy. The strongest evidence points to not smoking, moderating alcohol (especially heavy use), moving regularly, maintaining a healthy weight for your body, and managing conditions like thyroid disease or diabetes with your clinician—not through internet protocols.\n\nChange works best in layers: pick one shift for four weeks—earlier bedtime, weekday walks, switching to half-caff—before adding another. Partners can adopt changes together so one person is not policing the other. Shared goals feel less like punishment and more like teamwork.\n\nBe wary of extreme detoxes, unregulated supplements, or social media routines that promise miracles. Ask your clinic before starting new herbs; some interact with medications. Quality sleep and stress care belong on the same list as nutrition—they are not separate moral categories.\n\nLighthouse believes in sustainable habits, not punishment. You are building a foundation for pregnancy and for the life you will live however this path unfolds. Smoking cessation programs, alcohol moderation, and moving together as a couple can feel less isolating than solo discipline ever does. Small shifts you can keep beat dramatic overhauls you abandon after one hard week every time. Progress, not perfection, is always the real goal here now, truly.',

  'ivf-stimulation':
    'IVF stimulation uses injectable hormones to encourage multiple follicles to grow so eggs can be retrieved. Protocols vary—long, short, mini, or tailored based on age, AMH, and prior response. Monitoring visits with blood work and ultrasounds adjust doses; this phase is data-heavy and emotionally loaded for most people.\n\nSide effects like bloating, fatigue, mood swings, and tenderness are common. Ovarian hyperstimulation is a risk your team watches for; report sharp pain, rapid weight gain, or vomiting promptly. Clear your calendar enough for appointments, but keep small comforts: easy meals, a heating pad, a friend on text.\n\nPartners can help with mixing medications, organizing supplies, and documenting questions. If needles scare you, practice with a nurse or use numbing ice—skill grows quickly. You are allowed to hate the shots and still do them; both feelings can coexist without guilt.\n\nStimulation is a sprint within a marathon. Lighthouse encourages you to ask why a protocol was chosen and what trigger shot plan means for retrieval timing—you are an active participant, not a passive vessel. Follicle counts rise on ultrasound; estrogen blood tests guide dose changes throughout the phase. Knowing the plan reduces the helplessness that often rides alongside the needles. You are allowed to ask questions every visit.',

  'two-week-wait':
    'The two-week wait is the space between embryo transfer or insemination and the pregnancy test your clinic schedules. Progesterone support may mimic pregnancy symptoms—sore breasts, bloating, cramping—so symptom-spotting is unreliable. Many teams ask you not to test early because false negatives or positives create extra anguish.\n\nProtect your heart with boundaries: mute pregnancy announcement threads if you need to, plan one gentle activity per day, and decide in advance who gets news and when. A partner agreement on testing day can reduce miscommunication when emotions run high and words come out wrong.\n\nIf anxiety spikes, ground in what you control: hydration, rest, attending follow-up appointments, and compassionate self-talk. Distraction is not denial; it is coping. A short walk, a favorite show, or a nap can be medicine when your mind will not stop scanning for signs.\n\nThe wait is brutal because hope and fear sit side by side. Lighthouse honors that limbo—you do not have to perform calm to deserve care. Agree on who you will tell before beta day and what you will do if the result is negative: a movie, a walk, a day off work. Limbo is still living; you are allowed to protect your heart while you wait.',

  'failed-transfer':
    'A failed transfer is a specific grief: you held hope in a measured embryo and a carefully prepared lining, and the beta test still came back negative. It is not "just another negative"—it can shake faith in your body, your clinic, and the future you were already picturing.\n\nClinics may review endometrial receptivity, embryo quality, immune or clotting workups, or suggest another cycle with adjustments. Ask for a clear timeline and what "normal" recovery looks like before trying again. Bleeding or hormone shifts after stopping progesterone vary; call if pain is severe or fever develops.\n\nAllow anger, numbness, or jealousy toward others\' successes. Couples often grieve differently; schedule a debrief date to align before the next plan. You do not owe anyone a brave face while your heart is still catching up to the news.\n\nYou are not starting from zero—you are starting with more knowledge. Lighthouse walks with you through the post-transfer valley, reminding you that a negative test is an event, not your identity. Ask whether the embryo was tested, what the lining looked like, and if a hysteroscopy or ERA is reasonable before the next cycle. Rest between cycles is medical and emotional care, not delay for delay\'s sake.',

  'clinic-questions':
    'Good questions turn appointments into collaboration. Before your visit, write three priorities: diagnosis understanding, treatment options, and costs or logistics. Ask what success rates mean for people your age and diagnosis—not just clinic-wide billboards that blend every case into one hopeful number.\n\nClarify timelines: How long is this protocol? When is retrieval or transfer likely? What side effects should trigger a call? Who is on call after hours? Request written instructions for medications; photo them into your phone so you are not decoding handwriting at midnight.\n\nFinancial clarity prevents surprises: What is included in a cycle package? What are storage fees for embryos? What happens if cancellation occurs mid-cycle? If something feels rushed, say so—advocacy is appropriate, not rude. You are hiring expertise, not auditioning for care.\n\nBring your partner or a friend if allowed; two sets of ears catch more. Lighthouse believes informed consent includes emotional consent—you should leave knowing not just what to do, but why it matters for you. Write questions the night before; photo your medication sheet so nurses can verify doses. A good visit leaves you clearer, not more confused than when you walked in. Advocacy is part of good care, always and without apology.',

  'after-miscarriage-body':
    'After a miscarriage, your body needs time to finish what biology started. Bleeding may last days to weeks; cramps can come in waves. Hormones fall on their own schedule, which is why mood swings, fatigue, or breast changes can linger even when bleeding stops and friends assume you are "back to normal."\n\nFollow your clinician\'s guidance on when to test hCG again, when to try again, and when to seek urgent care—fever, heavy soaking pads hourly, or severe pain are red flags. Gentle movement, iron-rich foods if bleeding was heavy, and hydration support recovery without demanding heroics.\n\nSex, tampons, or baths may be discouraged briefly to reduce infection risk; ask what is safe for you. Periods often return in four to six weeks, sometimes later. Home pregnancy tests can linger positive while hCG falls—this is confusing but common, not a sign you imagined the loss.\n\nYour body is not betraying you; it is healing from a loss it also grieved. Lighthouse encourages rest without apology and follow-up care without shame—physical recovery deserves the same tenderness as emotional repair. Call your team if anything feels off; you do not need to minimize symptoms to be strong. Healing is not linear, and neither is bleeding, hormones, or grief.',

  'grief-no-timeline':
    'Grief after pregnancy loss does not follow a neat calendar. Anniversaries, due dates, a friend\'s baby shower, or a song in a store can reopen the wound years later. That does not mean you are "stuck"; it means love leaves traces that time softens but rarely erases completely.\n\nSome people name their baby; others prefer private remembrance. Rituals—planting, lighting a candle, writing a letter—can honor what was without forcing you to perform sorrow for others. There is no correct way to remember; only what feels honest to you on a given day.\n\nTherapy, support groups, and books on perinatal loss can normalize complex feelings like relief mixed with devastation, or jealousy toward your past self who felt hopeful. Hearing "at least it was early" from well-meaning friends can sting—your grief is valid regardless of gestational age.\n\nThere is no finish line you must cross to be healthy. Lighthouse holds space for grief that returns in waves, affirming that healing and remembering can coexist for as long as you need. Friends may rush you toward "trying again" or "moving on"; you set the pace, not their comfort. Your loss counts whether others saw a bump or only a line on a test.',

  'partner-grief':
    'Partners grieve pregnancy loss too, often quietly. You may feel you must stay strong, or that your pain is smaller because you did not carry the pregnancy. Pain is not a competition. Disenfranchised grief—when others overlook your loss—can deepen loneliness and make you question whether you are allowed to hurt.\n\nName what you are mourning: the future you imagined, the embryo you already talked to, the role you wanted. Share with your partner when you are ready; compare stories only to connect, not to rank. Different grief timelines are normal and do not mean you love each other less.\n\nPractical care still matters: handle calls to family, manage bills, remember dates that are hard. Also seek your own support—a friend, clinician, or group for partners—so you can show up without emptying your tank. You cannot pour from an empty cup indefinitely.\n\nLighthouse sees you as a full participant in this loss, not a backdrop. Your tears, anger, and hope belong in the story too. You may feel you should be the strong one; strength can include naming hurt aloud and asking for a hug when the due date passes quietly. You do not have to earn your grief with a medical role—it is yours because you loved.',

  'trying-again':
    'Trying again after loss is brave and complicated. Some people need one cycle to heal; others need months or years. There is no virtue in rushing, only in choosing with your body and heart aligned. Your timeline is not a referendum on how much you wanted the pregnancy that ended.\n\nA preconception visit can review whether testing is needed, if progesterone support is recommended, and what monitoring feels supportive versus triggering. Emotions may flare at ovulation, ultrasounds, or the first time you see a pregnant friend—plan comfort strategies before those moments arrive.\n\nTalk with your partner about how you will mark anniversaries, what you will tell others, and how to pause if anxiety spikes. It is okay to stop and resume. Trying again does not mean you have forgotten; it means you are making room for a future that still includes hope.\n\nLighthouse respects both caution and longing. Some clinicians suggest waiting one cycle; others clear you immediately—follow personalized guidance, not generic advice from forums. You are allowed to feel excited and terrified in the same breath; both belong in an honest conversation with your care team. Trying again is an act of hope, not disloyalty to the baby you lost.',

  'miscarriage-prevention':
    'Most miscarriages happen because of chromosomal changes in the embryo, not because you lifted something heavy or had coffee. That truth can feel unfair and relieving at once: unfair because you cannot control it all, relieving because guilt is often misplaced and cruelly heavy.\n\nEvidence-based prevention focuses on what helps overall health: treating thyroid or diabetes, taking folic acid, avoiding smoking, limiting alcohol, and managing conditions like antiphospholipid syndrome when diagnosed. Bed rest has not been shown to prevent loss. Prenatal vitamins support general health but do not erase all risk.\n\nRecurrent loss workups exist after defined numbers of losses and age considerations; ask rather than assume you must endure three times silently. When providers offer tests after loss, they are gathering information, not implying you caused the outcome through a single choice or moment.\n\nLighthouse replaces blame with clarity. You deserve information that empowers, not myths that punish your body for something it did not choose. Treatments like progesterone may be offered in specific contexts—ask why, for how long, and what evidence supports them for your situation. Compassion for yourself is part of prevention too—not just vitamins and lab work. You did not cause most losses; you deserve truth, not guilt.',

  'progesterone-folate':
    'Progesterone and folate play different roles, both important. Progesterone supports the uterine lining after ovulation and in many treatment cycles; supplementation may be recommended after loss, in luteal phase defect discussions, or during IVF. Take it as directed and ask about timing if you bleed.\n\nFolate (folic acid or methylfolate) helps prevent neural tube defects and supports cell division in early pregnancy. Start before conception when possible. Higher doses may be advised with certain medications or histories. Timing matters: progesterone often starts after ovulation or transfer; folate ideally begins weeks before conception.\n\nSide effects like sleepiness or constipation can be managed—report them instead of quitting silently. If you have MTHFR variants discussed online, let your clinician interpret what that means for your prescription rather than self-treating from forums. Blood tests can clarify absorption when needed.\n\nUnderstanding these medicines turns them from mysteries into tools. Lighthouse encourages questions at the pharmacy counter and the clinic—your protocol should make sense to you, not just to your chart. Progesterone routes include oral, vaginal, or intramuscular—side effects differ, and your team can help you choose. Folate belongs in the story before the positive test, not only after. Both medicines work best when you understand why you are taking them.',

  'recurrent-loss':
    'Recurrent pregnancy loss is commonly defined as two or more clinical losses, and evaluation may be offered earlier depending on age and findings. Workups can include uterine imaging, hormone and thyroid labs, autoimmune and clotting panels, genetic karyotypes for both partners, and embryo testing in IVF.\n\nResults sometimes show treatable issues; sometimes everything looks normal, which is maddening and oddly common. Normal tests do not mean your losses were insignificant—they mean science still has gaps. Emotional support groups for recurrent loss exist because the grief is cumulative and deserves its own language.\n\nTreatment paths may include surgery for uterine septum, aspirin or heparin when indicated, IVF with PGT-A, or supportive care with close monitoring. Second opinions are reasonable when you feel dismissed. Ask about chromosomal testing of products of conception when appropriate; you can request copies of all labs.\n\nYou are not broken for grieving repeatedly. Lighthouse validates recurrent loss as a medical and emotional crisis deserving thorough, compassionate care—not platitudes. Persistence is not pushiness—it is care for your future family and for the babies you already loved into being, however briefly. Each loss deserves its own mourning, even when the world expects you to be "used to it" by now.',

  'cervical-mucus':
    'Cervical mucus changes with estrogen through the cycle. After your period, dryness or scant sticky mucus is typical. As ovulation nears, mucus often becomes creamy, then wet, stretchy, and clear—sometimes described as egg-white. That fertile-quality mucus helps sperm swim and is a free, body-based signal.\n\nCheck mucus at the same time daily, before showering or using lubricants that mask texture. Not everyone sees obvious patterns, especially after recently stopping hormonal birth control or with hydration changes. After intercourse, seminal fluid can mimic fertile mucus for hours—check before sex or use clean fingers without lubricant.\n\nMucus observations pair well with ovulation tests: mucus predicts the fertile window; tests detect the LH surge. If mucus is always scant or blood-tinged mid-cycle, mention it to your clinician. Foul smell or green color is medical, not fertility tracking—do not ignore infection signs.\n\nLighthouse celebrates low-tech literacy. Noticing mucus is not gross—it is listening to a pathway your body already offers. Hydration and sinus medications can change mucus texture—note them in your log so patterns make sense when you review a month at a time. You do not need perfect observations every day—trends over weeks matter more. Simple tracking still counts as real, valuable self-knowledge.',

  'ovulation-tests':
    'Ovulation predictor kits detect luteinizing hormone (LH) surging before ovulation, usually 24–36 hours ahead. A positive test suggests ovulation is likely soon—time intercourse or insemination per your plan. Read instructions for your brand; some require testing at the same time daily after mid-cycle.\n\nLH can surge without ovulation, or peak across two days in some people. If you never get a positive, you may be testing too early or late, or you may not be ovulating—follow up medically rather than buying endless boxes. Some people test twice daily near mid-cycle when strips are cheap; others test once to reduce stress.\n\nWith PCOS, LH can be chronically elevated, making strips tricky; ultrasound monitoring may be clearer. False positives can occur with PCOS or perimenopause—follow up with blood progesterone or ultrasound if strips never match how you feel. Store tests away from humidity so lines stay readable.\n\nUsed wisely, OPKs add confidence; used obsessively, they add stress. Lighthouse supports your choice to test or to pair tests with clinician monitoring—your peace matters too. Test in the afternoon for some brands because LH surges vary; consistency beats guessing. If strips confuse you, clinic monitoring is a valid alternative, not a failure of effort.',

  'irregular-cycles':
    'Irregular cycles—shorter than 21 days, longer than 35, or varying widely—signal that ovulation may be unpredictable. Common causes include PCOS, thyroid issues, high prolactin, perimenopause, stress, significant weight change, or coming off hormonal contraception. One off cycle after illness is usually not alarming; patterns matter.\n\nTracking the first day of bleeding for three months gives your clinician a map. Blood work and ultrasound often clarify next steps; treatment might target thyroid, induce ovulation, or address insulin resistance. Athletes and people with low body fat may see ovulation pause; regain with nutrition support takes time.\n\nYou are not "bad at being a woman" because your calendar wobbles. Irregularity is a symptom, not a moral failing. Thyroid and prolactin labs are simple screens worth doing once irregularity persists. Birth control recently stopped can confuse patterns for months—note the stop date for your chart.\n\nLighthouse helps you bring data and dignity to the conversation. Regular cycles are not the price of admission to motherhood—understanding your pattern is. Bring three months of cycle lengths, even if they vary; that honesty helps your team move faster toward answers that fit your body. Irregular does not mean hopeless—it means worth investigating with care. Your chart is a clue, not a verdict.',

  'four-things-partners-need':
    'Partners often need four things: information, tasks, emotional language, and permission to feel. Information means learning the basics of your treatment so you can ask sensible questions without your loved one re-teaching every visit. Tasks mean reliable help with injections, calendars, insurance calls—chosen, not assumed.\n\nEmotional language means naming fear or sadness without fixing it. Try, "I am here," or, "Do you want to talk or distract?" instead of, "Stay positive." Permission to feel means your stress counts too; burnout helps no one. Research shows partners who proactively lift logistics report better relationship satisfaction during treatment.\n\nAsk, "What can I take off your plate this week?" and follow through without reminders. Predictability reduces anxiety: know injection nights and appointment days. Check in weekly about what is working—plans shift with cycles, and flexibility beats rigid heroics every time.\n\nLighthouse trains partners to be steady, not heroic. Showing up well is a skill you can practice together. You do not need to memorize every acronym; you need to show up curious, kind, and willing to learn when your person tells you what landed wrong last time. Consistency over months beats one perfect gesture on transfer day. Steady, humble presence beats spectacular every time.',

  'how-are-you':
    '"How are you?" can land like a doorbell during fertility treatment—well meant, exhausting to answer. If you are the supporting partner, try more specific questions: "How is your body feeling today?" "What do you need tonight—quiet or company?" "What should I handle so you do not have to?"\n\nIf you are the one being asked, it is okay to set scripts: "I am hanging in. Please do not ask for details unless I offer." "Today was hard because of the appointment; I do not want advice, just a hug." Fertility treatment can make small talk feel violent; protect each other at gatherings with a code word to leave early.\n\nWhen you do ask how they are, listen for answers beneath "fine." Reflect back what you hear: "It sounds like today felt lonely after the scan." Connection deepens when questions invite honesty, not performance. Replace vague check-ins with invitations that have an exit ramp—no one owes a TED talk about their ovaries at dinner.\n\nLighthouse champions conversations that make room for nuance—not forced cheer. Agree on a short phrase for relatives who mean well but pry: "We will share news when we have it." You can love people and still protect your story until you are ready to tell it on your terms.',

  'manage-your-anxiety':
    'Anxiety during fertility is a signal that something precious feels threatened—not a character flaw. Start with basics: sleep, movement, nourishment, and limiting late-night searches that turn one forum post into certainty of disaster. Name catastrophic thoughts and ask, "What is true today?" Often today you are safe, supported, and following a plan.\n\nTherapy, especially CBT, helps challenge all-or-nothing thinking. Grounding tools—5-4-3-2-1 senses, paced breathing, cold water on wrists—can lower panic in the moment. Medication is an option some reproductive psychiatrists support during treatment; ask if curious without shame.\n\nAnxiety can spike before providing a sperm sample or delivering bad news to family—anticipate those moments with a plan. Grounding in your senses for sixty seconds lowers panic enough to think. If you notice irritability toward your partner, repair quickly: "I am scared, not angry at you."\n\nYou can be anxious and still be capable. Lighthouse treats mental health as part of fertility care, not an obstacle to earning treatment. Name your triggers: blood draws, financial talks, family events—and build small rituals around them so your nervous system knows what comes next. Asking for help with anxiety is strength, not proof you are not ready to be a parent. Your feelings deserve a seat at the table.',

  'fertility-not-define':
    'Fertility struggles can shrink your identity to charts and blood tests. You are still a friend, artist, athlete, nerd, aunt, leader, lover—still someone with humor and opinions unrelated to ovaries or sperm. Reclaiming breadth protects you when results sting and the world feels like it only asks one question.\n\nSet small non-fertility goals: a book club, a hike, learning one recipe that intimidates you. Notice jealousy toward people without this worry and greet it with honesty, not shame. Create a shared list of topics that are off-limits on date night—period, embryos, money—for one evening a week.\n\nRemember why you chose each other before babies entered the conversation. If treatment pauses, use the pause to rebuild play, not only to regroup medically. Your partnership existed before clinics and deserves oxygen that is not measured in follicles.\n\nLighthouse refuses to let treatment consume your self-worth. You are navigating fertility; you are not only fertility. Keep friendships and hobbies that remind you who you were before treatment—and who you will be however this chapter ends. Your value was never stored in a follicle count or a beta number, and it still is not. You are whole while you wait, and worthy right now.',

  'intimacy-as-task':
    'When sex becomes timed to ovulation or scheduled around procedures, desire can fade and resentment can grow. This is common, not a sign your relationship is failing. Bodies are smart—they resist feeling like instruments, and minds follow. Naming the shift out loud is the first step toward redesigning closeness.\n\nRebuild intimacy in layers: non-sexual touch, making out without outcome, privacy from talk of mucus for one evening. Scheduled sex works better for some couples when you also schedule non-sexual affection daily—hug, hold hands, send a loving text. If pain is present, pelvic floor physical therapy may help before you force through.\n\nMedical teams can advise on safe lubricants and positions after procedures. Talk with your partner about performance pressure and grief. A therapist versed in sex and infertility can help you redesign closeness without blaming either person for a very human response to pressure.\n\nYou deserve pleasure and play, not only productivity. Lighthouse reminds you that intimacy is a relationship virtue—not a lab technique you must ace. Schedule connection that is not fertile-window sex: massage, shower together, slow kisses that do not owe anyone a outcome. Desire often returns when pressure lifts, even if that takes time and honest conversation.',

  'monthly-checkpoints':
    'Monthly checkpoints give your partnership a harbor in stormy months. Pick a consistent day—first Sunday, last Friday—to review logistics and feelings for thirty to forty-five minutes. Agenda lightly: upcoming appointments, medication changes, money worries, and one appreciation each. Keep it short enough that you will actually do it again.\n\nSeparate logistics from emotional debrief if mixing them leads to fights. Use "I" statements: "I felt alone at the ultrasound," not, "You never care." End with one shared plan: who calls insurance, what you will tell family, one fun thing to schedule. Rotate who facilitates so one partner is not always the therapist.\n\nCapture decisions in a shared note app to avoid "I thought you agreed" fights. If you are in IVF, include financial check-ins—money stress erodes connection silently. Sample questions: What felt lonely? What felt supportive? What do we need to drop this month?\n\nIf a month was too raw to meet, reschedule without guilt. The ritual matters more than perfection. Lighthouse champions structure that keeps love visible when medicine takes center stage. Checkpoints are not business meetings—they are acts of care that say: we are still a team, not just co-patients. Thirty minutes of honesty can carry you both through a brutal week.',

  'fertility-glossary':
    'Medical language can feel like a wall. AMH estimates ovarian reserve—not egg quality per month. AFC is antral follicle count on ultrasound. IVF retrieves eggs; ICSI fertilizes one sperm into an egg; PGT tests embryos for chromosomal normality. Beta hCG is the blood pregnancy test after transfer.\n\nLH triggers ovulation; FSH stimulates follicles. Luteal phase follows ovulation; priming suppresses hormones before stimulation. Endometrium is uterine lining; ERA tests receptivity in some cases. Blastocyst, morula, and cleavage-stage embryos reflect days of development—ask which day your lab cultures to.\n\nAntagonist, agonist, and microflare protocols are stimulation approaches with different timelines. You do not need fluency overnight. Save questions for nurses—they explain daily. Write questions next to terms you do not understand; clinics expect curiosity, not memorization before your first consult.\n\nThis glossary is a starting point, not a test. Lighthouse wants you to ask what words mean until they feel like tools, not judgments hiding in Latin. When you hear new acronyms, ask for plain language definitions and write them down in your own words so they stick. Nurses expect questions—asking is collaboration, not embarrassment. Every expert was once confused by the same abbreviations you hear in the clinic today too, honestly.',

  'age-and-fertility':
    'Age affects fertility because egg quantity and quality decline over time, especially after the mid-30s, with a steeper drop in the early 40s. That does not mean conception is impossible—odds change, they do not vanish. Sperm also changes with age, though more gradually, and male age still influences miscarriage risk somewhat.\n\nEarlier conversations with a clinician can clarify ovarian reserve testing, timeline options, and whether IVF or egg freezing fits your goals. Age-related risk also includes miscarriage and certain genetic conditions; screening options exist. Egg freezing preserves younger egg age, not unlimited futures—discuss realistic family size goals honestly.\n\nCompassion for yourself matters when social media shows later-in-life miracles without context. Societal clocks are cruel; your worth is not stored in follicles. Many families begin later with help or without, and "later" does not mean "less deserving" of support or respect.\n\nLighthouse speaks about age honestly—without scare tactics or false promises. You deserve data to plan, and compassion for the feelings data stirs. Egg quantity declines; quality matters for chromosomal balance in embryos—both are worth discussing, not just one headline number from a blood test. Your timeline is personal, not a race against strangers online. Age informs planning; it does not cancel hope.',

  'see-a-specialist':
    'Knowing when to see a reproductive endocrinologist can save months of guessing. Many guidelines suggest evaluation after 12 months of trying if under 35, after 6 months if 35 or older, or sooner with known issues: irregular cycles, endometriosis, PCOS, prior cancer treatment, two losses, or concerns about sperm.\n\nA specialist visit is history, exam, and targeted tests—not instant IVF. Bring cycle notes, past labs, and surgery records. Ask what diagnosis they suspect and what least-invasive next steps look like. Bring a list of cycle lengths, prior pregnancies, surgeries, and STI history so nothing gets lost in a rushed intake.\n\nAsk what their clinic\'s live birth rate is for your age group, not only pregnancy rate. If you feel dismissed, seek another office—fit matters. Insurance and geography complicate access; telehealth and teaching hospitals may help. Advocates and nurses can clarify referrals when your primary care doctor hesitates.\n\nSeeking help is strength, not surrender. Lighthouse cheers early questions—your timeline deserves respect. Expect an hour of history, exam if indicated, and a plan—not instant IVF. You are gathering a team, not failing a test you should have passed alone. The right specialist listens as carefully as they orders labs. Early visits save months of guessing alone.',

  'youre-not-alone':
    'Infertility can feel like whispered failure while everyone else posts ultrasound photos. You are not alone: millions face difficulty conceiving, and communities exist online and in person where honesty is welcome. Roughly one in six couples experience infertility—many suffer quietly because shame makes it look rarer than it is.\n\nSharing selectively can lighten the load—one friend, one group, one therapist. You choose the depth. Hearing others\' stories normalizes shots, waiting rooms, and ambiguous results without ranking whose pain counts more. Professional support does not mean you are failing—it means the load is heavy and you are human.\n\nIf communities trigger comparison, it is okay to step back. Support should steady you, not rank your pain. Connection reduces shame even when outcomes stay uncertain. You can belong to people who understand without telling your whole story to everyone at the office holiday party.\n\nLighthouse is built on connection without toxic positivity. However this path unfolds, you belong to people who understand the mix of science and sorrow—and who will sit with you in it. Loneliness is a symptom of silence, not proof that you are the only one struggling. Reaching out is often the bravest thing you do in a given week.',

  'talking-about-infertility':
    'Talking about infertility is choosing who enters your story. You owe no public narrative. With family, short scripts help: "We are working with doctors and will share news when ready." With work, know your leave policies; you may not owe colleagues details about embryos, sperm counts, or insurance battles.\n\nDecide with your partner what is private—sperm counts, financial strain, donor choices. Surprises hurt when one person overshares. Social events may require pre-planned exits when pregnancy announcements appear. You can ask close friends not to share ultrasound images in group chats without asking you first.\n\nWorkplace allies can run interference with nosy coworkers if you brief them privately. If silence feels heavy, one trusted person can carry the weight with you. Therapists offer neutral space. You can change your mind about how much you share as treatment evolves—boundaries can move with you.\n\nDisclosure is a skill, not a virtue test. Lighthouse supports boundaries that protect your heart while keeping room for support you actually want. Scripts help: "We are working with doctors and will update when ready." You can love people and still decline to educate them about your uterus at Thanksgiving. Privacy and connection can coexist when you choose both deliberately.',

  'online-communities':
    'Online communities can be lifelines—IVF groups, loss spaces, PCOS forums—offering practical tips and 2 a.m. solidarity. Look for moderation, clear rules against medical misinformation, and respect for diverse outcomes including child-free paths. The right room feels like exhaling, not performing bravery for strangers.\n\nProtect yourself: limit trigger-heavy threads before appointments, block unkind voices, and verify advice with your clinic. Photos of needles and beta lines are common; comparison is optional. Bookmark threads that explain monitoring appointments or medication mixing—practical help beats fear stories that assume your cycle will mirror theirs.\n\nAvoid groups that rank suffering or shame IVF. Curate your feed like you curate your clinic team: intentionally. Consider one community for education, another for feelings. Leave when it stops helping. Private accounts let you participate without broadcasting to coworkers who do not need front-row seats.\n\nLighthouse values peer support with eyes open. The right corner of the internet can make you feel seen; the wrong one can convince you catastrophe is inevitable. Choose rooms that leave space for hope and realism—where "me too" does not require "only bad news ahead." Log off when the feed stops feeling like support and starts feeling like surveillance of your body. Your nervous system matters as much as your feed.',

  'same-sex-options':
    'Same-sex couples build families through paths shaped by biology and law: donor sperm with IUI or IVF, reciprocal IVF where one partner provides eggs and the other carries, surrogacy where legal frameworks allow, adoption, and foster care. None is "better"—each has costs, timelines, and emotional textures worth naming honestly.\n\nStart with a reproductive clinic experienced in LGBTQ+ care and a lawyer versed in parentage establishment. Insurance coverage varies widely; ask early about benefits and grants. Second-parent adoption or court orders may still be required even if you are on the birth certificate—budget legal fees before you begin.\n\nSome states ban surrogacy for same-sex couples; research before committing funds. Friendship networks with kids can feel triggering—pace your exposure. Stories from other couples can illuminate, but your family will be its own shape, not a copy of someone else\'s highlight reel.\n\nLighthouse affirms that your love is sufficient ground for parenthood. Options expand every year; you deserve providers who use your names and pronouns with respect. Legal parentage varies by state and pathway—lawyers early, always, even when the medical plan feels straightforward on paper. Building a family as a same-sex couple is normal, even when paperwork is not. Your family deserves competent, respectful care from day one.',

  'same-sex-medical':
    'Medically, same-sex family building often centers donor gametes and precise timing. IUI places washed sperm into the uterus around ovulation; IVF creates embryos in the lab and may include PGT-A. Reciprocal IVF links one partner\'s genetics to the other\'s body—beautiful and logistically detailed in equal measure.\n\nScreen donors for health history, genetic panels, and legal contracts. Sperm banks provide known or anonymous donors; home insemination has legal and safety considerations—clinician guidance matters. Ask clinics if they have LGBTQ+ liaisons or training for front-desk staff so you are not educating them while grieving a negative beta.\n\nSperm shipping timing matters—coordinate with the lab to avoid cancelled cycles. Document every homophobic comment and escalate; you deserve safe care. Monitoring, medications, and two-week waits mirror heterosexual IVF emotionally even when the intake forms finally get your family structure right.\n\nMedicine should serve your family vision, not retrofit it. Lighthouse helps you ask sharp questions about success rates with donor sperm, embryo ownership, and birth certificate processes in your state. Reciprocal IVF requires coordination on stimulation and legal parentage for the non-genetic parent from day one. You deserve clinics that see your family before you have to explain it. Inclusive care is not a bonus—it is baseline.',

  'same-sex-stories':
    'Hearing other same-sex couples\' stories can loosen fear\'s grip. Some conceive quickly with donor IUI; others need IVF, egg or embryo banking, or surrogacy journeys spanning years. Loss, failed transfers, and financial strain appear here too—queer paths are not immune to grief or waiting rooms at dawn.\n\nLook for narratives that include partners, donors, and chosen family. Notice what helped: lawyers early, therapists, employers with fertility benefits, friends who showed up with meals. Stories include using one partner\'s eggs and the other\'s uterus, using a relative\'s sperm with legal counsel, or fostering while waiting for IVF.\n\nFinancial strain and joy coexist in these narratives. Let community remind you that family is built many ways. Your story will not copy theirs. Comparison steals joy; inspiration fuels planning when you borrow ideas, not timelines.\n\nLighthouse curates stories as mirrors, not scoreboards. However you become parents—or choose not to—you remain the author of a life that matters. Stories include IUI success after several tries, IVF with PGT, surrogacy across states, and adoption alongside biology—each valid, each demanding its own kind of courage. Borrow hope, not timelines, from what you read. Your path will have its own turns, pace, and deeply sacred timing always.',

  'solo-first-steps':
    'Choosing solo parenthood is intentional, brave, and logistical. First steps often include clarifying your timeline, budget, and support network. Schedule a reproductive consult to discuss donor IUI versus IVF, age-related planning, and fertility preservation if you want flexibility before you commit to a path.\n\nLegal counsel helps with donor contracts and parentage. Think through disclosure to future children, backup guardians, and who will be at appointments when you need a ride after retrieval. Consider who will be your emergency contact for retrieval and who can advocate if you are sedated.\n\nReflect on how you will answer "Where is dad?" or "Where is your other parent?" with age-appropriate honesty over time. Financial planners familiar with fertility can map multi-year costs including storage fees and multiple attempts. Emotions can mix excitement and doubt; both belong.\n\nLighthouse honors single parents-by-choice as full families in the making—not "second best" versions of someone else\'s plan. Budget for multiple IUI or IVF attempts, storage fees, and legal consults. Choose who will be listed on birth certificates and who will be godparent-level support before needles start. Solo does not mean without community—it means choosing your village on purpose. You are building a family by design, not by default.',

  'solo-ivf':
    'Solo IVF typically uses donor sperm—fresh or frozen from a bank—with your eggs retrieved after stimulation. You will choose a protocol based on ovarian reserve, decide on PGT-A if age or history suggests, and plan for embryo storage fees. One healthy embryo might lead to transfer; others remain frozen for siblings or later attempts.\n\nThe physical load is yours alone, which makes support planning essential: a friend for post-retrieval rides, meal trains during stimulation, childcare if you already parent. Financially, compare clinic packages, medication pharmacies, and grants for single parents. Embryo disposition forms ask hard questions—read them with a friend, not alone at midnight.\n\nIf you face OHSS risk, know warning signs before retrieval. Solo parents often build two support tiers: practical helpers and emotional confidants. Emotional peaks hit during the two-week wait; line up who gets the call about your beta before you are too raw to choose.\n\nYou are both patient and project manager. Lighthouse cheers arrangements that treat your time and body as precious—because they are. You will sign consents alone—read them slowly. Asking for help is part of the protocol, not a sign you are not ready to do this on your own terms. Solo IVF is demanding; planning support is wisdom, not weakness.',

  'solo-support-system':
    'A support system for solo fertility is not luxury—it is infrastructure. Map roles: who accompanies you to procedures, who knows your medication schedule, who can talk on hard nights. Include at least one person outside the journey—a friend who reminds you that you exist beyond treatment and still deserve fun.\n\nPractical lists help: pharmacy delivery, pet care during retrieval, backup work coverage. Online solo-parent communities offer templates for donor choice and disclosure language. Church, gym, or work friends may offer help you have not requested—practice saying yes before you are too depleted to ask.\n\nFrozen meal chains after retrieval are common in parent groups; ask someone to organize yours. Therapy can process shame about doing it "alone" when you are choosing courage, not settling for less. If family is complicated, chosen family counts fully.\n\nLighthouse believes nobody should white-knuckle this alone. Asking for help is evidence of wisdom, not weakness. Rotate helpers for injections, childcare pickup, or meal trains so no single friend burns out—and so you learn early that community parenting starts before the baby arrives. Your village can include people who will never hold a needle but will hold you. Support is part of the plan, not a footnote.',

  'co-parenting-early':
    'Co-parenting arrangements—raising a child with someone who is not a romantic partner—need clarity early. Discuss values, discipline, religion, geography, finances, and how decisions will be made before anyone is pregnant. Lawyers draft agreements covering insemination roles, parental rights, and dispute resolution while goodwill is still abundant.\n\nMedically, decide whose gametes, whose uterus, and which donor or surrogacy path. Clinics still require screenings and counseling. If one person provides sperm and another carries, parentage laws vary—do not assume goodwill covers legal status when a birth certificate alone may not protect the non-biological parent.\n\nDiscuss what happens if one co-parent moves away, partners with someone new, or disagrees about medical care. School pickup, medical consent, and holiday splits should be explicit. Mediation upfront is cheaper than litigation with a child in the middle. Communication rhythms matter: monthly meetings, shared documents, therapy check-ins.\n\nLighthouse treats co-parenting as a valid family form deserving the same seriousness as any fertility plan—because children thrive when adults align before conception, not after conflict arrives. Chemistry as co-parents is as important as chemistry as friends; liking each other on paper is not enough for eighteen years of decisions. Hard conversations now prevent harder ones in the pediatrician\'s waiting room.',

  'donor-conception':
    'Donor conception—eggs, sperm, or embryos from someone else—opens parenthood to many paths. Donors may be anonymous from a bank or known to you; each has genetic, legal, and emotional implications. Clinics screen for infectious disease and often genetics; contracts clarify future contact rules before vials ship or cycles begin.\n\nChildren may have half-siblings via sperm bank limits; ask how many families share a donor. Disclosure to children is widely encouraged by psychologists, paced age-appropriately. Some families do sibling searches through banks when children share donors—decide your comfort level early, not when a teenager asks unexpected questions.\n\nLaws on anonymity vary by country and are changing. Counseling helps adults separate donor liking from parenting readiness. Grief for a genetic link you imagined is normal, even as gratitude for donors grows. Therapy helps hold both without forcing you to pick a single emotion.\n\nLighthouse speaks openly about donor conception without secrecy or shame. Your family\'s love defines parenthood; genetics are one thread in a larger weave. Counseling for donors and recipients is standard—use it. Questions about telling your child, telling relatives, and telling yourself all deserve airtime. Donor paths are common, even when nobody at brunch mentions them. Secrecy rarely ages well; honesty can be planned with care.',

  'surrogacy-2025':
    'Surrogacy in 2025 spans gestational carriers—implanted with embryos not genetically theirs—and traditional surrogacy, less common today. Laws differ by state and country; intended parents need reproductive lawyers before matching. Agencies coordinate screening, mental health evals, and insurance, though independent journeys exist for those with strong legal teams.\n\nMedical steps often include IVF to create embryos, then transfer to a surrogate after legal clearance. Costs include agency, legal, medical, compensation, and insurance premiums. Ethical surrogacy centers informed consent, fair compensation, and ongoing support for carriers—not extraction, not secrecy, not rushed matches.\n\nCarrier psychological screening protects everyone. Intended parents should plan for NICU costs even when hoping for term birth. Post-birth orders differ by county—lawyers local to the delivery hospital matter as much as the clinic you chose for retrieval. Emotional complexity touches everyone: longing, autonomy, future children\'s questions.\n\nLighthouse tracks evolving regulations and ethical conversations so you can pursue surrogacy with eyes open—honoring carriers as partners in creation, not instruments. Match through agencies or trusted referrals; verify insurance for pregnancy complications. Understand compensation, travel, and legal parentage orders pre-birth so surprises do not arrive in the delivery room. Surrogacy is a relationship, not only a contract. Respect and clarity protect everyone involved.',

  'pcos-fertility':
    'PCOS affects ovulation, metabolism, and sometimes self-image. Not everyone with PCOS struggles to conceive, but irregular ovulation can lengthen trying. First steps often include weight-neutral lifestyle support, checking thyroid and prolactin, and discussing medications like letrozole or clomid to induce ovulation when you are ready.\n\nInsulin resistance may benefit from movement, nutrition patterns, and sometimes metformin. Egg quality and quantity are often reassuring in PCOS; the challenge is triggering reliable ovulation. Inositol is discussed online; bring studies to your clinician rather than starting alone. Hirsutism and acne are valid symptoms to treat for quality of life, not vanity.\n\nIVF is available if oral meds fail or other factors appear. Mental health matters—PCOS diagnosis stories can carry shame that is unwarranted. You are not "broken ovaries" in a search result; you are a person whose hormones need a tailored map, not a one-size-fits-all lecture about weight.\n\nLighthouse meets PCOS with science and kindness. Your body is not a problem to defeat; it is a system to understand and advocate for. Weight-neutral care still addresses insulin resistance when present. Pregnancy with PCOS is common with support—do not let headlines scare you away from asking for help. You deserve care that respects your whole self, not only your ovaries.',

  'pcos-tracking':
    'Tracking with PCOS can feel noisy: long cycles, multiple LH surges on strips, or absent ovulation signs. Start with period first days, then add one method—temperature, mucus, or OPKs—and see what is readable. Ultrasound monitoring during medicated cycles is often clearer than home tests alone when your body sends mixed signals.\n\nApps may mis-predict fertile windows if their algorithms assume 28-day cycles. Customize cycle length ranges and note medication starts. Continuous glucose monitors are optional tools some find enlightening, not required. Exercise you enjoy beats punishing workouts you quit; sustainability matters more than heroics.\n\nIf medicated cycles begin, home strips may conflict—follow clinic instructions over app predictions. Weight, sleep, stress, and glucose swings can shift patterns; log them lightly without obsession. Celebrate any data you gather; imperfect logs still help clinicians more than a blank page and shrug.\n\nLighthouse encourages tracking that serves you. If charts spike anxiety, clinics can monitor instead—you are allowed to outsource the detective work. Cycle apps assuming 28 days will mislead you—customize or ignore predictions. Your peace is part of the protocol, not a bonus prize for perfect charts. Data should reduce confusion, not become a second full-time job. Track on your terms, or let your clinic track for you.',

  'endo-fertility':
    'Endometriosis—tissue similar to uterine lining growing outside the uterus—can affect fertility through inflammation, adhesions, and anatomical changes. Not everyone with endo is infertile, but many need multidisciplinary care. Surgery may help some, harm others; decisions should be individualized with a specialist who explains expected benefits for your stage and family goals.\n\nSymptoms like painful periods, pain with sex, bowel or bladder flares, and fatigue deserve treatment regardless of baby plans. Suppressing periods hormonally may conflict with trying; talk timing with your team about whether to operate, medicate, or pursue IVF first. Document pain patterns so clinicians see the full picture, not only fertility labs.\n\nIVF may bypass some tubal issues but does not erase endo pain. Pelvic physical therapy, mental health support, and pain specialists belong on the team. Ask explicitly how endo might affect implantation and what monitoring will look like if you conceive—advocacy includes pain care and family-building at once.\n\nLighthouse validates endo as real, often invisible, and deserving belief. You are not exaggerating—you are reporting. Strong advocacy combines pain care with family-building plans so neither gets dismissed. You deserve providers who treat your pain as seriously as your follicle count, because both shape your life now. Endo and fertility can be addressed in the same conversation—you do not have to pick one.',

};
